#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:167
msgid ""
"`#1367 <https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest/issues/1367>`_: **Support for "
"subtests** has been added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:169
msgid ""
":ref:`subtests <subtests>` are an alternative to parametrization, useful in "
"situations where the parametrization values are not all known at collection "
"time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:171 ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:663
#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:782
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:173
msgid ""
"def contains_docstring(p: Path) -> bool:\n"
"    \"\"\"Return True if the given Python file contains a top-level "
"docstring.\"\"\"\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_py_files_contain_docstring(subtests: pytest.Subtests) -> None:\n"
"    for path in Path.cwd().glob(\"*.py\"):\n"
"        with subtests.test(path=str(path)):\n"
"            assert contains_docstring(path)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:186
msgid ""
"Each assert failure or error is caught by the context manager and reported "
"individually, giving a clear picture of all files that are missing a "
"docstring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:188
msgid "In addition, :meth:`unittest.TestCase.subTest` is now also supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:190
msgid ""
"This feature was originally implemented as a separate plugin in `pytest-"
"subtests <https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest-subtests>`__, but since then "
"has been merged into the core."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:194
msgid ""
"This feature is experimental and will likely evolve in future releases. By "
"that we mean that we might change how subtests are reported on failure, but "
"the functionality and how to use it are stable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:197
msgid ""
"`#13743 <https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest/issues/13743>`_: Added support "
"for **native TOML configuration files**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:199
msgid ""
"While pytest, since version 6, supports configuration in ``pyproject.toml`` "
"files under ``[tool.pytest.ini_options]``, it does so in an \"INI "
"compatibility mode\", where all configuration values are treated as strings "
"or list of strings. Now, pytest supports the native TOML data model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:203
msgid ""
"In ``pyproject.toml``, the native TOML configuration is under the ``[tool."
"pytest]`` table."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:205
msgid ""
"# pyproject.toml\n"
"[tool.pytest]\n"
"minversion = \"9.0\"\n"
"addopts = [\"-ra\", \"-q\"]\n"
"testpaths = [\n"
"    \"tests\",\n"
"    \"integration\",\n"
"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:216
msgid ""
"The ``[tool.pytest.ini_options]`` table remains supported, but both tables "
"cannot be used at the same time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:218
msgid ""
"If you prefer to use a separate configuration file, or don't use ``pyproject."
"toml``, you can use ``pytest.toml`` or ``.pytest.toml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/changelog.rst:220
msgid ""
"# pytest.toml or .pytest.toml\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"minversion = \"9.0\"\n"
"addopts = [\"-ra\", \"-q\"]\n"
"testpaths = [\n"
"    \"tests\",\n"
"    \"integration\",\n"
"]"
msgstr ""

